$showPartialCorrectAnswers=1;
Context()->variables->are(x=>'Real',y=>'Real',t=>'Real');
Context()->strings->add("conservative"=>{},"not conservative"=>{});

$r = random(1,10);
$x1 = Formula("$r*t");
$y1 = Formula("0");
$x2 = Formula("$r*cos(pi*t/2)");
$y2 = Formula("$r*sin(pi*t/2)");
$x3 = Formula("0");
$y3 = Formula("$r(1-t)");


BEGIN_TEXT
Let C be the boundary of the region bounded by the x-axis, the quarter-circle with radius $r, and the y-axis oriented counterclockwise starting from the origin. 
If we label the edges of the boundary as \(C_1,C_2,C_3\) starting from the bottom edge going counterclockwise. Then the edges are parameterized as(\(0\leq t\leq 1\) ):
$BR
\(C_1\)
$BR
\(x_1(t)=\) \{ans_rule(20)\}
$BR
\(y_1(t)=\) \{ans_rule(20)\}
$BR
\(C_2\)
$BR
\(x_2(t)=\) \{ans_rule(20)\}
$BR
\(y_2(t)=\) \{ans_rule(20)\}
$BR
\(C_3\)
$BR
\(x_3(t)=\) \{ans_rule(20)\}
$BR
\(y_3(t)=\) \{ans_rule(20)\}
$BR
\(\displaystyle\oint\limits_C y^2xdx+x^2ydy = \int\limits_{C_1} y^2xdx+x^2ydy +
\int\limits_{C_2} y^2xdx+x^2ydy+
\int\limits_{C_3} y^2xdx+x^2ydy\)
$BR
\(\hskip{77pt} = \)\{ans_rule(18)\} + \{ans_rule(18)\} + \{ans_rule(18)\}
$BR 
Applying Green's theorem,
$BR
\{ BeginTable(center=>0).
      Row(['\(\displaystyle\oint\limits_C y^2xdx+x^2ydy = \)', tableintegral(width=>1),tableintegral(lowerwidth=>1,upperwidth=>7),ans_rule(15),'\(dxdy =\)',tableintegral(width=>1),ans_rule(15),'\(dy=\)',ans_rule(20)],separation=>1).
   EndTable();
\}
$BR
The vector field \(F=f(x,y)i+g(x,y)j\) is:\{ pop_up_list(['conservative','not conservative']) \}
END_TEXT
## C_1...C_4
ANS($x1->cmp());
ANS($y1->cmp());
ANS($x2->cmp()->withPostFilter(AnswerHints( 
  Formula("$r*cos(t)") => "Right idea, but will this be at the right point when t = 1? Change your frequency.",
)));
ANS($y2->cmp()->withPostFilter(AnswerHints( 
  Formula("$r*sin(t)") => "Right idea, but will this be at the right point when t = 1? Change your frequency.",
)));
ANS($x3->cmp());
ANS($y3->cmp());

# \int_C_1...
ANS(Compute("0")->cmp);
ANS(Compute("0")->cmp);
ANS(Compute("0")->cmp);


# \int\int
